---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
import styles from '../../styles/GuidePage.module.css';

const pageTitle = 'Days Between Two Dates: A Practical Guide with Examples | Age Calculator Pro';
const pageDescription =
  'How to count the exact number of days between two dates, why inclusive vs exclusive endpoints matter, and where the calculation is used in real life.';
const pageKeywords = 'days between dates, calculate days between two dates, day counter, inclusive dates';
const canonical = 'https://agecalculatorpro.app/guides/days-between-dates';

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'Days Between Two Dates: A Practical Guide with Examples',
  description: pageDescription,
  datePublished: '2026-06-23',
  dateModified: '2026-06-23',
  author: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Age Calculator Pro Editorial Team',
    url: 'https://agecalculatorpro.app/about-us',
  },
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Age Calculator Pro',
    logo: { '@type': 'ImageObject', url: 'https://agecalculatorpro.app/favicon.svg' },
  },
  mainEntityOfPage: canonical,
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title={pageTitle}
  description={pageDescription}
  keywords={pageKeywords}
  canonical={canonical}
  schemas={[schema]}
>
  <Header />

  <main>
    <section class={styles.hero}>
      <div class="container">
        <h1>Days Between Two Dates: A Practical Guide with Examples</h1>
        <p>
          Counting the days between two calendar dates sounds trivial. In practice, hotel bookings, contract periods, project
          plans, and legal filings each define "days between" slightly differently. This guide walks through the conventions.
        </p>
        <div class={styles.metaRow}>
          <span class={styles.badge}>Editorial team</span>
          <span class={styles.badge}>Published June 23, 2026</span>
          <span class={styles.badge}>5 min read</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <div class="container">
        <article class={`card ${styles.article}`}>
          <h2>The two conventions</h2>
          <p>
            When you ask "how many days between June 1 and June 4?", there are two defensible answers depending on how you treat
            the endpoints.
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Exclusive of both ends (the "difference" answer)</strong> - June 1 to June 4 is 3 days apart. This is what a
              date-subtraction operation returns and what our calculator uses.</li>
            <li><strong>Inclusive of both ends (the "counting" answer)</strong> - June 1 to June 4, counting both, is 4 days. This
              is what hotels and rental agreements often use when they say "your stay is 4 days".</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Which one is correct depends on the question. Neither is universally right - they answer different things.
          </p>

          <h2>Where each convention shows up</h2>
          <div class={styles.tableWrap}>
            <table class={styles.table}>
              <thead>
                <tr><th>Context</th><th>Typical convention</th><th>Why</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>Age calculation</td><td>Exclusive (difference)</td><td>You have lived through the days between the two calendars, not the birthday itself twice.</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Hotel stays</td><td>Inclusive nights</td><td>A "3-night" stay checks in on day 1 and checks out on day 4 - three nights slept.</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Legal notice periods</td><td>Varies - read the statute</td><td>Some jurisdictions include the day the notice is served, others do not.</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Project deadlines</td><td>Usually exclusive of start day</td><td>"You have 30 days to respond" typically means 30 clear days after today.</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Loan interest</td><td>Depends on the contract</td><td>Some loans use "actual days" between dates; others use a 360-day year convention.</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <h2>Worked examples</h2>
          <h3>Trip planning</h3>
          <p>
            Suppose you are flying out on August 12 and returning on August 20. If you ask "how long is the trip?", most people
            answer 8 days (August 20 minus August 12), and that is the exclusive convention. But if you count the days you will
            be away (both endpoints), you get 9. Airlines, tour operators, and travel insurance policies each use one or the other -
            check the fine print.
          </p>

          <h3>Contract notice</h3>
          <p>
            If a contract says "either party may terminate on 30 days written notice", and notice is served on May 5, the
            termination date is not automatically June 4. Depending on jurisdiction, the notice period may exclude the day of
            service, in which case day 1 is May 6 and termination is June 5. When timing is important, ask a lawyer - or at
            least read the definition of "notice period" in the contract's interpretation section.
          </p>

          <h3>Simple age gap</h3>
          <p>
            When our calculator says two dates are "3 days apart", it uses the exclusive convention: it counts the transitions
            from midnight to midnight. That is the same convention every mainstream operating system uses when subtracting one
            date from another.
          </p>

          <h2>How to compute it in your head</h2>
          <p>
            For dates within the same month: subtract the day numbers.
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>June 10 to June 25 = 25 - 10 = 15 days.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            For dates across two months: count the days remaining in the first month, plus the day number of the second.
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>June 25 to July 4 = (30 - 25) + 4 = 5 + 4 = 9 days.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            For anything longer or across leap years, it is faster to use the calculator.
          </p>

          <h2>Using the age-difference tab</h2>
          <p>
            The age-difference tab on <a href="/#calculator">the calculator</a> doubles as a days-between calculator. Enter the
            two dates (they do not have to be dates of birth), and the result shows the exact number of years, months, and days
            between them. If you want just the total day count, multiply the year and month spans out - or read the raw day
            difference in the exports.
          </p>

          <h2>Common bugs to avoid</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Off-by-one from time zones.</strong> If one date is stored as a timestamp in UTC and the other as a local
              calendar date, you can lose or gain a day. Always compare dates as calendar dates, not timestamps.</li>
            <li><strong>Off-by-one from inclusive vs exclusive counting.</strong> Decide up-front which convention the question is
              asking about.</li>
            <li><strong>Approximating "30 days" as a month.</strong> Some months are 28, 29, 30, or 31 days. If precision matters,
              count actual days.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Related reading</h2>
          <p>
            For a deeper look at the year-month-day math involved in age calculation, see
            <a href="/guides/how-age-is-calculated">How Age Is Calculated</a>. For the leap-year rules that quietly affect long
            spans, see <a href="/guides/leap-years-and-age-calculation">Leap Years and Age Calculation</a>.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class={styles.related}>
      <div class="container">
        <div class={styles.relatedGrid}>
          <article class={`card ${styles.relatedCard}`}>
            <h3>How Age Is Calculated</h3>
            <p>The full calendar-arithmetic algorithm.</p>
            <a href="/guides/how-age-is-calculated">Read guide -&gt;</a>
          </article>
          <article class={`card ${styles.relatedCard}`}>
            <h3>Leap Years and Age</h3>
            <p>How our engine handles February 29 and long multi-decade spans.</p>
            <a href="/guides/leap-years-and-age-calculation">Read guide -&gt;</a>
          </article>
          <article class={`card ${styles.relatedCard}`}>
            <h3>Age for Official Documents</h3>
            <p>Passport, school, and job-form conventions worth double-checking.</p>
            <a href="/guides/age-calculation-for-official-documents">Read guide -&gt;</a>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
